).
</emphasis>
Ventrals 140–149 notched with weak keels (
<quantity box="[588,713,547,573]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5814" metricValueMax="3.7084" metricValueMin="3.4543999999999997" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" unit="in" value="141.0" valueMax="146.0" valueMin="136.0">136–146 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, M. A." box="[719,849,547,573]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref34041" refString="Smith, M. A. (1943) The Fauna of British India, Ceylon and Burma, including the whole of the Indo-Chinese Subregion. Reptilia and Amphibia. Vol. 3. Serpentes. Taylor. &amp; Francis, London. 584 pp." type="book" year="1943">Smith 1943</bibRefCitation>
); subcaudals 70–84 divided (
<quantity box="[1165,1262,546,573]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9177" metricValueMax="2.1844" metricValueMin="1.6509999999999998" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" unit="in" value="75.5" valueMax="86.0" valueMin="65.0">65–86 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, M. A." box="[1269,1400,547,573]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref34041" refString="Smith, M. A. (1943) The Fauna of British India, Ceylon and Burma, including the whole of the Indo-Chinese Subregion. Reptilia and Amphibia. Vol. 3. Serpentes. Taylor. &amp; Francis, London. 584 pp." type="book" year="1943">Smith 1943</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,506,582,609]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Maxillary arch dentition.</emphasis>
Arched with a dip towards diastema; 12 teeth perpendicular to maxilla, curving inwards; prediastemal teeth 7, postdiastemal teeth 5, observable gradual tooth size increase in prediastemal tooth set with the largest teeth precursing diastema; diastema around 3 postdiastemal tooth-sockets wide; suffixed with 3 smaller teeth followed by last grooved pair of large teeth (
<figureCitation box="[801,878,691,718]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1833,1857]" captionTargetBox="[250,1338,181,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-17@15.[250,1338,181,1809]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Ahaetulla lineages in Peninsular India and Sri Lanka showing side-by-side comparison of their superficial head morphology and maxillary dentition. (From the top) (a) Ahaetulla farnsworthi sp. nov. (b) A. isabellina comb. nov. (c) A. malabarica sp. nov. (d) A. borealis sp. nov. (e) A. nasuta (f) A. oxyrhyncha comb. nov. (g) A. sahyadrensis nom. nov. (h) A. travancorica sp. nov. (i) A. dispar &amp; A. travancorica sp. nov. (j) A. perroteti (1) Ahaetulla farnsworthi sp. nov. (2) A. isabellina comb. nov. (3) A. malabarica sp. nov. (4) A. borealis sp. nov. (5) A. nasuta (6) A. oxyrhyncha comb. nov. (7) A. pulverulenta (8) A. sahyadrensis nom. nov. (9) A. dispar (10) A. travancorica sp. nov. (11) A. perroteti." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423530/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 6j</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,429,726,752]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Colouration in life.</emphasis>
Dorsum bright to darker shades of green (in males) to dark brown to olive (in females); supralabials light green to bronzed, distinct and separated by a weak pre-ocular stripe that extends till the end of the jaw angle; body darker than the head; venter with light green to dirty white central strip bordered with lighter stripes ventrolaterally; eyes golden with numerous black speckles that are highest in concentration towards the ends of the pupil, pupil distinct from the rest of the eye with a light yellow halo around the pupil (also see 
<bibRefCitation author="Ganesh, S. R. &amp; Chandramouli, S. R." pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="19 - 24" refId="ref31927" refString="Ganesh, S. R. &amp; Chandramouli, S. R. (2011) On the nomenclature and taxonomy of the south Indian colubrid snake Ahaetulla perroteti (Dumeril, Bibron &amp; Dumeril, 1854). Herpetological Bulletin, (117), 19 - 24." type="journal article" year="2011">Ganesh &amp; Chandramouli 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,536,942,968]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Colouration in preservative.</emphasis>
Dorsum faded green to faded brown with mildly distinct supralabials; post-ocular stripe distinct; venter faded light green to dirty white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,510,1014,1041]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Distribution and Habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dumeril, Bibron &amp; Dumeril" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[521,737,1015,1041]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Ahaetulla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perroteti">
<emphasis box="[521,737,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Ahaetulla perroteti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in the upper reaches of the Nilgiri Hills. This species was recorded from the Mukurthi National Park where it occurs at high elevations, from 1980 msl to 2300 msl (
<figureCitation box="[208,294,1086,1113]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1395,1940]" captionTargetId="figure-488@45.[151,1435,1173,1940]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 25. Habitat of Ahaetulla perroteti, Mukurthi Hills, in the upper Nilgiris (in the Nilgiri district, Tamil Nadu State, India) showing montane shola grasslands." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423581" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423581/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). Unlike its other congeners, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dumeril, Bibron &amp; Dumeril" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[629,758,1087,1113]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Ahaetulla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perroteti">
<emphasis box="[629,758,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A. perroteti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is predominantly terrestrial to semi-arboreal, inhabiting the montane grasslands and the shola forest mosaic of the Upper Nilgiris.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
